Leviton LDATA / LWHEM — Hubitat Driver
A Hubitat Elevation driver for the Leviton Smart Load Center (LDATA / LWHEM), porting the excellent rwoldberg/ldata-ha Home Assistant integration to Hubitat's Groovy driver framework.
Monitor your electrical panel, track per-circuit power usage, and (optionally) remotely trip or reset 2nd-gen smart breakers — all from Hubitat.

Supported Hardware
DeviceSupportLeviton LDATA Smart Breaker Data Hub (1st gen)✅ FullLeviton LWHEM / LWHEM-2 Whole Home Energy Monitor (2nd gen)✅ FullLeviton 1st Gen Smart Circuit Breakers✅ Monitoring onlyLeviton 2nd Gen Smart Circuit Breakers (with Remote On/Off)✅ Monitoring + ControlLeviton CT Clamp Sensors (LSMMA — Grid, Solar, Generator)✅ Monitoring

Not supported: Legacy LDATA panels without LWHEM. Standard (non-smart) breakers show no data — this is expected; they have no electronics.


Features

Real-time updates via WebSocket connection to the Leviton cloud (same transport as the My Leviton app)
REST polling fallback for energy counters and panels where WebSocket doesn't deliver all data
Per-breaker child devices with power, current, voltage, frequency, energy, and switch state
CT clamp child devices for whole-home energy sources (Grid, Solar, Generator)
Remote breaker control — trip or reset 2nd gen breakers from Hubitat automations (optional, off by default)
Bandwidth keepalive — automatically sends the same panel wake signals the official app uses
Auto-reconnect — WebSocket reconnects automatically on disconnect
Leg-aware data mapping — correctly handles leg 1 / leg 2 panel positions and 2-pole breakers


Files
FileDescriptionLevitonLDATA_Parent.groovyParent driver — install this firstLevitonLDATA_Child.groovyChild driver — install this second

Installation
Step 1 — Install the Child Driver

In Hubitat, navigate to Drivers Code
Click + New Driver
Paste the entire contents of LevitonLDATA_Child.groovy
Click Save

Step 2 — Install the Parent Driver

Click + New Driver again
Paste the entire contents of LevitonLDATA_Parent.groovy
Click Save

Step 3 — Create the Parent Device

Navigate to Devices
Click Add Device → Virtual
Give the device a name (e.g. Leviton Panel)
Set Type to Leviton Smart Load Center LDATA Parent
Click Save Device

Step 4 — Configure Credentials

Open the newly created device
In Preferences, enter:

My Leviton Email — your login email for the My Leviton app
My Leviton Password — your password


Optionally configure poll interval and breaker control (see Preferences)
Click Save Preferences

The driver will authenticate, discover your panel(s), and automatically create child devices for every smart breaker and CT clamp sensor. This may take 30–60 seconds on first run depending on panel size.

Preferences
PreferenceDefaultDescriptionMy Leviton Email—Your My Leviton account emailMy Leviton Password—Your My Leviton account passwordREST Poll Interval60sHow often to poll the REST API for energy counter data. WebSocket handles real-time power updates; this fills in energy (kWh) fields. Options: 30 / 60 / 120 / 300 secondsAllow Breaker ControlOffEnables the Switch capability on breaker child devices, allowing remote trip/reset. Read the safety notes below before enabling.Enable Debug LoggingOffLogs detailed driver activity to the Hubitat logEnable WebSocket Message LoggingOffLogs every raw WebSocket message. Useful for debugging; verbose in normal use

Child Devices
The parent automatically creates one child device per smart breaker and one per CT clamp.
Breaker Child Device Attributes
AttributeUnitDescriptionswitchon/offBreaker closed (on) or tripped/open (off)powerWReal power draw on this circuitamperageARMS currentvoltageVLine voltage (sum of both legs for 2-pole)frequencyHzLine frequencyenergykWhCumulative energy consumption (hardware counter, firmware-dependent)energyConsumptionkWhSame as energy — cumulative consumptionenergyImportkWhImport energy (relevant for solar/generation breakers)breakerState—ManualON, ManualOFF, TrippedremoteState—RemoteON, RemoteOFFcanRemoteOn—true if this breaker supports remote reset (2nd gen only)ampRatingABreaker's rated amperageposition—Panel slot position (1–66)leg—Panel leg (1 or 2)poles—1 for single-pole, 2 for double-polebreakerModel—Hardware model stringbreakerId—Internal Leviton device ID
CT Clamp Child Device Attributes
AttributeUnitDescriptionpowerWActive power (positive = consuming, negative = generating)amperageARMS currentenergykWhCumulative energyenergyConsumptionkWhCumulative consumptionenergyImportkWhCumulative importchannel—CT port number on the LWHEMctId—Internal Leviton CT ID
CT names (Grid, Solar, Generator, etc.) come from what you configured in the My Leviton app.

Remote Breaker Control

⚠️ Read this section carefully before enabling breaker control.

Enabling Allow Breaker Control in preferences adds Switch capability to breaker child devices:

off (Switch Off) = TRIPS the breaker — cuts power to that circuit immediately
on (Switch On) = RESETS the breaker — restores power to that circuit

Important safety notes

Only 2nd generation Smart Circuit Breakers with canRemoteOn = true support remote reset (on). 1st gen breakers can be tripped remotely but must be manually reset at the panel.
Tripping a breaker via automation is permanent until reset — it is not like turning off a smart switch. Anything on that circuit loses power instantly.
Do not create automations that trip breakers on a schedule or in response to unrelated triggers without careful consideration.
The canRemoteOn attribute on each child device shows whether that breaker supports remote reset.
Breaker control always goes through the Leviton cloud — it will not work if your internet is down or if Leviton's cloud is unreachable.


Architecture
Hubitat Device: Leviton Smart Load Center LDATA Parent
│
│  Manages: Authentication, WebSocket, REST polling, panel discovery
│
├── Child: Panel Breaker — Kitchen (LDATA-BREAKER-abc123)
├── Child: Panel Breaker — Master Bath (LDATA-BREAKER-def456)
├── Child: Panel Breaker — HVAC (LDATA-BREAKER-ghi789)
│   └── (one child per smart breaker)
│
├── Child: CT — Grid (LDATA-CT-panelId-1)
└── Child: CT — Solar (LDATA-CT-panelId-2)
    └── (one child per configured CT clamp)
Data flow
Leviton Cloud
    │
    ├── WebSocket (real-time)  ──→  parse() ──→ handleWsNotification()
    │                                              └──→ update child devices
    │
    └── REST API (scheduled)   ──→  restPoll() ──→ bandwidth toggle
                                                    └──→ GET breakers + CTs
                                                         └──→ update child devices
WebSocket is the primary data source — it mirrors exactly what the My Leviton app receives. The driver subscribes to every panel, breaker, and CT individually, just like the official app.
REST polling runs on a configurable schedule as a fallback and to retrieve energy counter fields (energyConsumption, energyImport) that are only available via REST on some firmware versions.
Bandwidth keepalive — every 45 seconds the driver sends PUT bandwidth:1 to each panel. This is the same signal the My Leviton app sends to keep the panel actively pushing data to the cloud. Without it, the panel goes idle and stops sending WebSocket updates.

Firmware Notes
FirmwareBehaviourv1.x (LDATA)Energy counters are lifetime cumulative values. REST poll needed for energyConsumption.v2.0+ (LWHEM)Energy counters reset with each bandwidth toggle (period counters, not lifetime). Driver uses real-time power from WebSocket for energy tracking.v2.1.0 (LWHEM-2)Bandwidth toggle causes 10–20s cloud reconnect. Driver includes settle delays and retries.
The driver detects firmware version automatically from the panel data and adjusts behaviour accordingly.

Troubleshooting
No child devices created

Check the Hubitat log for [LDATA] messages
Verify your email/password are correct in Preferences
Confirm your panel appears in the My Leviton app and is listed as Connected (green)
Make sure your Hubitat hub has internet access

"Auth Failed" in wsStatus attribute

Your My Leviton credentials are incorrect, or
Your account uses Two-Factor Authentication (see below)

Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)
This driver does not support 2FA interactive prompts. If your My Leviton account has 2FA enabled:

Log into the My Leviton web app or mobile app
Temporarily disable 2FA in your account security settings
Save Preferences on the Hubitat driver to trigger a fresh login
You may re-enable 2FA after — the driver caches the session token and will only need to re-login if the token expires (~60 days)

WebSocket keeps disconnecting

Check that your Hubitat hub's outbound connection to socket.cloud.leviton.com port 443 is not blocked by a firewall
Enable Debug Logging and watch the Hubitat log for reconnect messages
The driver will automatically reconnect with exponential backoff

Power shows 0W for all breakers

The panel may have gone idle. Click Refresh on the parent device to trigger a REST poll and bandwidth wake-up
Confirm the panel shows Connected in the My Leviton app

Child devices show stale data

Check the lastUpdate attribute on the parent device
Click Refresh on the parent to force a REST poll
Enable Debug Logging to see whether WebSocket messages are being received

Deleting and re-discovering devices
Use the Delete Children command on the parent device to remove all child devices, then click Refresh to rediscover. This is useful after renaming breakers in the My Leviton app.

Known Limitations

Cloud-dependent — all operations go through Leviton's cloud API. Local LAN control is not available.
No 2FA support — accounts with two-factor authentication require temporary 2FA disabling (see above).
Energy counter accuracy — on v2.x firmware, per-breaker energy counters are period counters that reset with each bandwidth toggle. Lifetime energy tracking via REST is only reliable on v1.x firmware.
CT energy on v2.x — CT energy counters on LWHEM-2 panels are similarly unreliable. Power (watts) from WebSocket is accurate; cumulative kWh figures should be treated as approximate.
1st gen breaker reset — 1st gen smart breakers can only be tripped remotely. Physical reset at the panel is required to restore power.
Rate limiting — the driver enforces a minimum 10-second gap between login attempts to respect Leviton's API rate limits.


